I want to be a social worker. I will work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I will help children who are abused or neglected. I will also help troubled families. My values are service, respect, being good, and helping improve relationships. I want to improve my work skills too.

I always wanted to help others. I did not know the best way to do this. In high school and college, I saw people ignore their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. This made me study Psychology. After college, I was not sure what to do. One day, I met a boy who was scared. His parents were abusive. I talked to the police about him. I was there when they talked to his parents. The parents were not helpful. This made me think about social work.

Social justice is important. Society says all people are important. But, we often want to be like others. I am unique. I do not like being like others. In school, I stood up for what I believed. I colored my hair, wore special clothes, and joined GSBA. I fought against racism and discrimination. I will always stand up for social justice.

This paper talks about two models of sleep problems called insomnia. The biological model looks at genes and health. The sociocultural model looks at how people's environment affects their sleep. The review talks about these models and explains how each study helps us understand them. It also talks about the strengths and weaknesses of these studies.

A sleep problem can be a primary sleep problem, a problem linked to another mental problem, or a problem caused by other things. Primary sleep problems are called dyssomnias or parasomnias. Dyssomnias are problems with falling asleep or staying asleep. Parasomnias are sleep disorders with unusual behaviors or physical changes. Sleep problems linked to another mental problem are caused by mental disorders. This review focuses on insomnia and some other primary sleep problems in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep problems focuses on genes and the body's natural ways of controlling sleep. Neurons in the brain's hypothalamus control sleep and wakefulness. These neurons have a chemical called orexin. A study with mice found special receptors on these neurons that control sleep and wakefulness. When the receptors are activated, they help a person sleep. If they don't work right, this can cause sleep problems. The study also found that the results in mice can happen in people too. This means that sleep problems can be caused by both genes and the environment. If these receptors don't work right, it can lead to sleep problems without medication. The sociocultural model of this study is that if a person inherits these receptors, it can help them sleep. If they change, it can cause sleep problems and affect their everyday life.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it defines the disorder. Then, it explains how to diagnose it. Finally, it tells teachers how to help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

CAPD is a problem with how the brain processes what we hear. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain does not work well at separating sounds or understanding speech. This problem was first called "auditory imperception" in the 1950s.

Several tests can diagnose CAPD. Doctors or speech therapists may use these tests to see how well a person can understand sounds. There is no one test that always works.

CAPD can cause many problems, like not being able to hear sounds in space or understand speech. Teachers can help a student with CAPD by:
- Using clear, simple language.
- Speaking slowly and clearly.
- Writing things down.
- Testing the student often to see how they are doing.

Twelfth Night: Deception and Gender
Twelfth Night shows that hiding is good for some things but not forever. People must stop hiding or lose themselves. Stopping deception can make people feel alone. People may react differently when they find out they've been tricked. Some will be OK. Others will be mad.

Deception in gender role reversal is hard. It makes people ask why. In "Twelfth Night," Viola thinks she needs to be a man to stay safe. She does, but she feels alone. Olivia loves Viola as a man. This is confusing.

Viola and Orsino have feelings for each other too. This might be because Viola looks different. Olivia loves Viola as a man but then loves her as family. This shows Olivia is not like others who only like people for looks.

German colonial rule is known for being very cruel. It caused a genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. This is not the only way to describe the whole German colonial empire. The empire's policies and ruling styles were different in each place. The education given to people in colonies was also different. When the British took German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found many educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by writers at that time.

In South West Africa (now Namibia), the education of native people was mostly done by mission societies. The government did not do much. This was different from East Africa, where the government played a big role in education. The government did send more money to schools for Europeans. These education policies had long-term effects on South West Africa. Even after German rule ended, many people in South West Africa were not educated. This was because of many reasons. This study will talk about these reasons and look at new research on the thoughts of settlers and colonial leaders about native Africans.

There are many books about education in the German colonial empire. Most of these books are in German and were written in the early 1900s. These books describe the education systems in the colonies. Later books in English compared the education in different German colonies. These books showed big differences in the education systems. Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa is the most important book about this subject. Cohen talked about the differences between the education systems of these two colonies and the reasons for these differences. According to Cohen, the big number of settlers in South West Africa made the education system different.

South West Africa had a moderate climate, but much of it was desert. The European population in South West Africa was bigger than in other colonies. In 1913, there were nearly 15,000 whites in South West Africa, while there were only 5,336 in East Africa, the colony with the next biggest settler population.

Metal music has many types. There are so many that it's hard to list them all. Each type has many smaller types. Heavy metal is one of the most diverse and interesting types. It started 40 years ago. People made many smaller types of heavy metal. Today, there are many smaller types within these smaller types. This makes it hard to know what heavy metal is. It has taken ideas from other types of music. It started from somewhere. To understand heavy metal today, you need to know what it is and why it is a movement, not just a type. Metal is a movement. It is loud and dark. It has many feelings, but they are mostly dark. People in metal bands are good at playing their instruments. Many metal songs have words about drugs and dark feelings. Some people think the Beatles made the first heavy metal song. It was called "Helter Skelter". It was on the White Album and was a response to a Rolling Stones song.

Henri Rousseau, before the Surrealists, painted his dreams. The Dream, his 1910 painting, shows a woman in awe of her dreamland. This is also like Rousseau’s own dreams. He dreamed of love from other artists and art lovers. He was in a hard choice. He could copy others to be accepted, or stay unique. The Dream shows this struggle.
Henri Rousseau was born in Laval, France on May 21, 1844. His father sold things. Rousseau had no art training. He worked as a customs inspector. He lost his wife and many children. He wanted a new life. He painted to feel better. He was like an artist from the people.
Rousseau wanted the art world to love him. But he was not like other artists. He was not educated and started late. Others were famous too. Matisse was one. He was different. Matisse wanted to paint well. Rousseau wanted to paint well to be accepted. (Gordon, 92)

Many people think that ethics and aesthetics are connected. I think there is a reason for this. John Keats says, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn many things in life from education or experience. But we understand ethics and aesthetics without being taught like this. Both ethics and aesthetics try to explain, not tell us what to do. We try to explain why something is beautiful or moral, not how to make good art or be good. Criticism of art or morals can't fully describe what is good. We often can't explain why we like something, like the Mona Lisa. Even if we describe it well, there is still something more. Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Ethics and literature are like this. Wittgenstein says, "Ethics is transcendental." I think both ethics and art have a special power because they can't be fully explained. They affect us in a way that can't be fully explained. Literature becomes even more powerful because it has a moral quality. Immanuel Kant says, "Living involves values. . . . Literature is important because of the values we find there." So, I think ethics and art are closely connected because they affect us deeply and can't be fully explained.

Germany is strong today. It is united. It has its own culture. This culture comes from many places. It starts in München, near the Alps. It goes to Kiel, near the Baltic Sea. It goes from Köln on the Rhine River. It goes through the center of Germany. It goes to Dresden, on the Elbe River.

Germany was the home of the Germans. The name comes from the Germanic tribe called Tungrians. They were known as Germans before they fought the Gauls. Julius Caesar used the word "Germanus" to describe them. He took the word from the Gauls.

The origin of the name is not clear. Some say it came from a spear called a ger. Others say it came from the Old Irish word garim, meaning "to shout."

Tacitus wrote about the Germans in AD 98. He said they were originally from Germany. He said they did not mix with other races. They came by ship. They did not go to Germany for better land or weather. They did not go for conquest.

Germans lived on the border of the Roman Empire. They traded with the Romans. They served in the Roman army.

I looked down and saw the picture. I did not understand. I saw the bowl of fruit. It was big. I could not think about it. I wanted to draw. I had a book. It taught me how to draw. It told me to look at things in a simple way. Like a bowl of fruit in a simple frame. I looked at the bowl. I could not do it. I was very surprised. An artist told me to try. I used my hand. I tried to move the bowl. It was stuck. I used a mop. I cleaned the bowl. I thought about the picture. I felt good. I was happy. I cleaned the toilet.

Teenagers are dying when they drive. Many things make this happen. The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving. Lack of experience is also a big problem. This causes more accidents, including rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens have more accidents when they drive with friends. A study in Southern California showed this. More passengers mean more accidents.
Many states have tried to make teens safer by limiting driving hours and not letting other teens ride with them. But these rules are not enough. Teens are not ready to drive safely. A psychologist says 18 is too young. USA Today says teens like to take risks for fun. This means we should wait until they are older to give them a regular driver's license.
Many more teens will start driving in the next few years. A law could help. Schools could teach driving but no one under 18 could drive. A provisional permit could still be given, but more training would be needed. This could be like other states. A national law could protect teens everywhere.

I looked at many old Edison films in Library of Congress. There were fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use editing tricks to create illusions. I studied how these films use story and tricks. Most trick films are set in one place. The camera does not move. The films use long and medium shots, not close-ups. This style comes from theatre and vaudeville. In 1900, a film called Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel shows actors move side-to-side. The camera does not follow them. The camera stays in one place, like in a theatre. Most early trick films are one long shot. This makes them short, about a minute or less. They often show simple tricks like magic. Some films combine many shots to make one trick look real. The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) is such a film. The viewer sees only one shot, but there are many shots in one trick.

John Taylor from Caroline was early and strong supporter of the Republican Party. He was also farmer. His work and short time in politics made him known for his strong belief in personal freedom and government. He thought farming was best way to live. He tried to protect and encourage farming.

Taylor believed America had chance to make best government because it had no old ways to stop them. He thought people had natural rights. These rights must be strong and not controlled by government. He said 'state of nature' meant strong people and smart people won. But in society, this must not be.

To make good society, Taylor said government must be good. He thought government must be strong and careful. He said, "As government is done by people, all its good and bad must be human." He thought good government must protect property, help farming, and stop bad business. Government must be strong to stop evil in people. But government must be careful not to add bad rules.

Taylor wanted government to follow the Constitution very carefully. He wanted small government with only powers written in the Constitution. He knew big government could be bad. He thought simple rule of the Constitution could be bad, too. He thought the Declaration of Independence was true law of America because it said America was group of states.

In Figure 17, there was a big drop in commuter log submissions in March. It was a bit sad. We don't know why this happened. Maybe because it was winter. People don't commute by bike or by foot. December is the end of the fall semester. People are busy finishing schoolwork. They might forget about the commuter log. December is also busy with holidays. People don't need to come to campus. Classes start again in January. This might explain the low number of logs in February. The project had a big start. But then the energy went down. We made a special week in March to fix this. It was the Carpool Challenge Week. It helped a little. But it was hard to keep the project going. People like driving their cars. It's a big part of our culture. So, we gave out prizes. We gave gift cards for food, coffee, books, and so on. We could have given bigger prizes like bikes or cars. This might have helped more. The prizes were the same the whole time. Maybe if they got bigger over time, it would have helped. The gift cards were good at first. But if we had told about the big prizes in December and January, people might have been excited to participate more.

An ETF is like a security that follows an index, a commodity, or many assets. It is like an index fund, but it trades like a stock. ETFs give you many stocks at once and can be traded easily. They are cheaper than mutual funds. But, you must pay a commission to trade them. There are many kinds of ETFs. To check if they are good, you should look at the top 10 holdings. Here are the top 10 holdings of the ETF IHF.

In order to check if these stocks are good for the ETF, we compare their % and Beta. A Beta is a measure of risk. The ETF has higher Beta than the top 10 holdings. This means the top 10 holdings are less risky. The ETF has a higher return than the top 10 holdings. To see if these portfolios are different, we check the standard deviation. This is a measure of risk. If they are different, we will know.

Poe calls his poem "Dream-Land" one of his best. In this poem, he uses the word "Thule" twice. This word is from Virgil's writing. Virgil wrote about an island north of Britain. Some people think Poe got this from a more current source, such as his interest in German authors like Goethe. Goethe's poem "King of Thule" is like Poe's "Dream-Land". They have similar stories about a king who loses his wife and becomes very sad. Poe reads Goethe's poem in "Dream-Land". Poe's poem also uses "ultma Thule". This phrase is like an end to the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" are like companion poems. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes Thule as dark and lonely. This is like the king in "The King of Thule". Poe might have read Goethe's work because he admired Tennyson. Tennyson also liked Goethe.

In California, can a person hurt after slipping on applesauce in a store be given money for punitive damages? The person must show the store manager acted with bad intent. The manager may be found to have acted with bad intent if he knew the spill could hurt someone and did nothing to stop it.

Jennifer Palmer can say that the manager should have known about the danger because many people slipped in the store before. She may have a hard time showing the manager acted badly, but it is still possible.

On October 13, 2009, an employee told the manager about the spill, but the manager did not clean it up. Another employee also told the manager about the spill, but he did not clean it up either. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and hurt her back.

California law says a person can be given punitive damages if the person acted with bad intent, fraud, or malice. This means the person must have intended to cause harm or acted with a bad attitude. The law also says conduct is malicious if the person knew it could harm someone and did not stop it.

Four years ago, I took Islam class at CBC. We discussed if Islam is hostile. The question is still important now. After 9/11, media changed its view of Islam in America. In 2001, no presidential candidate with Muslim background, like Barack Obama, could have been elected.
The story of Muhammad is interesting. It says he was a martyr and people came to him. He multiplied food for forty men, like Jesus. This makes Muhammad seem like Jesus. This is bad because it makes Jesus seem less special.
The stories in the biography seem like proof of people converting to Islam. But, many stories are told by other people. This makes them seem less true.
I don't like how the book makes Muhammad seem like a godly, humble man. History shows he was not gentle. This makes me wonder if Muslims know the real story of Muhammad's power.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs were quickly changed after his life. As time passed, Christianity moved away from Jesus' original ideas. The world today shows a strong trend towards progress and change. Many people still follow the old teachings, but they may not be powerful enough to stop this change. In the future, many Christians will want to learn more about Jesus' real thoughts. They will remove later changes from Christianity, like layers of a cake. This will happen slowly, maybe over many years. When this happens, people will follow Jesus' ideas more closely. The church will be strong to lead this change. But, there will be less diversity in beliefs and practices. People will become more similar to each other. History has seen big changes before. For example, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, but later, the Roman Empire became Christian. The future will see a big change in Christianity, trying to find the original teachings. It is important to read Jesus' words as meanings, not just as literal words. What happened after Jesus' life? If we look far into history, we find only Judaism, the start of Christianity. Monotheism, a religion with one God, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were the core of the religion when the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people did not have one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and most were common people.

I think The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish and only care about themselves. They want to make their lives better, but not care for others. The book shows this in many ways. One way is the factory owners. They only want to make their companies big. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets hurt. They do not care about the smoke from the factories or the dirty water around the town. The owners also do not care about their workers. They want to make more money. They make workers work long hours and may fire many at once without paying or helping them find new jobs. During this time, there were no laws to help workers. So, the owners could make workers work in bad conditions. The book does not say it, but people in Packingtown were expected to live and work like this. There were no places for help. Some unions tried to help, but they often made money from the workers. Workers were treated very badly and had no way to leave. They were like slaves, always living on the edge of hunger and depending on mean bosses.

Many authors use different ways to make readers feel or think about important things. Some ways are better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these ways in his book The Great Gatsby. He often uses words that do not usually go together to make readers feel a certain way. He also gives special meaning to colors and uses them to do the same thing. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald builds up meaning for colors like white/gray and red/pink. Then he uses these colors to remind readers of feelings about important things.

White/gray means the same thing in Fitzgerald's book. White is nicer and higher class, while gray is older and faded. He shows this meaning at the beginning of the book. Everyone is often in white; Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a white shirt, and Catherine is powdered milky white. The only time people are not in white is when Nick is meeting Gatsby's party: "the halls are gaudy with bright colors." Fitzgerald also uses white/gray to show unimportance or uniformity. He does this with Daisy.

After a long time, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in a little white roadster. This makes readers see Daisy as less important, like something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this technique with Daisy many times to show this. There is a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar" and she is in a white dress before Tom and Gatsby's fight.

San Diego County has nice weather for growing plants. Many things grow there: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. People in San Diego want organic food. There are many organizations with long waiting lists for organic food. Many farms offer tours and places for hiking and birdwatching. This kind of farming can help the environment and make money.

Organic farming can help animals and plants by not using chemicals. But it is harder and costs more. It needs more work to keep away pests and weeds. It also takes more time to grow. Big farms can do more with less. Some work that helps animals and plants but is not organic farming also costs more.

The land in this story is near Potrero, California. It is 160 acres. There are different kinds of plants and animals there. Some are rare. People lived there a long time ago. The land was used for cattle and wood. Now, a farm on this land can help the environment.

I found this land on a real estate website. I looked at government programs to see how a small farmer can save money and help the environment. I found an organic farm in the same area as a model.

Culture is important in any negotiation. Culture is not the same everywhere. It is not one thing. It can be different in one country or city. It can also change from one company to another. A negotiator should not make big generalizations about a culture. For example, not all Russians are stubborn, and not all Japanese are easy to talk to. Instead, the negotiator should understand what the culture means for the negotiation. If the negotiator is in a foreign country, they should learn about the local culture and respect it. This can help with the negotiation. The negotiator should also understand the company's culture. Some companies work long hours, and others are more relaxed. The company's culture can affect how people communicate and work. Values are also important. They tell why people do things. For example, if saving face is important, the negotiator should not do anything that makes someone lose respect. The negotiator should learn about their opponent's personal culture too, to make the negotiation better.

Some people say, "There is no God." The Bible says this in Psalm 14. St. Anselm and St. Thomas Aquinas both believed in God. We want to compare their arguments. To do this, we assume they both are right about God. They both talk about the God in the Bible. We will look at their ideas. Neither gives a complete reason for believing in God. We will start with St. Anselm's idea. He says that God is in our minds. If we think of God, we cannot think he does not exist. We don't need other proof. This is what Christians call faith. St. Thomas Aquinas has a different idea. He says we can prove God with reason and evidence. This would be good for making new Christians. He gives five reasons. He says God is needed to make things change, cause things, and be better. If something is better than others, God must exist.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born. He would become known as Buddha. His life's work led to Buddhism's creation. Theravada Buddhism is the main type of this religion. It has been around for more than 2500 years. It is different today than when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, there is a yearly water-cutting ceremony. Monks and non-monks take part. It has meaning, even though Buddha did not teach about it.

Buddhist teachings have changed over time. This happened because of both help and harm from inside and outside the community. Today, we will use some special words. Internal forces come from Buddhists, regardless of if they are monks or not. External forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces harm or try to harm Buddhists. Benign forces do not harm Buddhists but can still affect them. These words will be used often in this discussion.

First, let's talk about Buddhism's main ideas. They seek help from three things: Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is made up of Buddhist texts. There are three types of texts: Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has what Buddha said. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for living. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has big ideas like no soul, suffering, and everything changing. These ideas help people escape the cycle of death and rebirth. When people become enlightened, they stop desiring, hating, and becoming confused. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks and laymen. The four main ideas in Buddhism are: life is suffering, attachment causes suffering, suffering can be ended.

The United States and Mexico had a long-lasting fight. This fight lasted from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War. The United States won and took Texas and the American Southwest. Many other fights happened between the two countries. These fights ended before the First World War. The fight started because of different beliefs and interests. This is like other countries that fight with their neighbors. Only Mexico and Cuba had long-lasting problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States. Religious differences caused problems. Sally Frahm said, "In the 18th and 19th centuries, Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy." The United States and Mexico had a fight because of their different beliefs. This fight was like the Cold War but between countries with different religions. The fight began because of the bad feelings between English and Spanish. The fight ended when Mexico depended on the United States and when American goals changed to economic help, not taking more land.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly got sick. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I needed safety and security. As a child, I heard, "You'll always find work, people will always get sick." So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or journalist, I became a nurse.

Now, I am 46 years old. I am single, no money, and can't work. I live on Social Security Disability. I have no savings. Every day, I struggle and feel unsafe. I know I couldn't survive these years without family and friends helping me.

Life has emergencies, big and small. No one can overcome everything alone. We need to learn to help each other, not just rely on big government.

Conservatives say Americans are strong and independent. But, our country's success was not about rugged individualism. It was about compassion, respect, and sharing resources. Pioneers did not travel alone.

Prepare for emergencies. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, food, and water. Learn your neighbors. Trust them. Build a community.

Why do organisms change in certain ways? What stops them from changing in other ways? Even in 1917, scientists said that we do not understand how simple shapes change in math. Now, we use math to study how mollusks make their shells. Our project uses math to learn how these changes happen. We look at X-ray pictures of a shell called Prunum. We find ways to measure parts of the shell. We use a computer program to make different shell shapes. These shapes help us understand how shells change. We look at how these changes happen. We also study how changes happen in real life.

A shell is like a tube that grows in a circle. These circles are called whorls. They go around a central line called the columella. The fastest-growing part of the shell is the largest part, called the body whorl. The part with all the whorls except the last is called the spire. The top of the spire is the apex, and the bottom is the base. The animal comes out of the shell through a hole called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different sides. They can be seen from the top (apical view), bottom (basal view), hole side (apertural view), and the other side of the hole (abapertural view). The most common way to see a shell is the apertural view, with the hole facing the viewer and the top pointing up.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top. Then, find where the first line starts. Divide the shell into two parts with this line. Count the whorls from this line, and estimate a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of holes that change over time. You can trace a line for these holes using the center of each whorl's hole and the hole's width and height. This line can be shown with math. Once you have a math formula, you can change some things and see how the mollusk's shell changes.

The rate of baby deaths in Indonesia has not changed much for ten years. The country has made good progress on some Millennium Development Goals, like water and sanitation. But the rates of health improvement for children and mothers are not good enough to meet the goals by 2015. We will discuss the reasons for this below. We need to strengthen the health system, not just focus on special programs.

Indonesia has more births with a skilled health worker, 72%. But this includes traditional workers who cannot help if the pregnancy is complicated. This leads to many maternal deaths. Also, fewer children under five are getting health care for diarrhea. Postnatal care is a problem too, with low rates everywhere.

Cesarian-section rates are low, about 4%. The rates are higher in cities (7%) and lower in rural areas (2%). This shows that healthcare is better in cities. Also, the poor have a harder time getting care, likely because of costs.

Next, we need to decide how to fix the healthcare system. Should we make special programs or strengthen the whole system? Special programs can be good because they have clear goals and can show results quickly. But they can also cause problems. They can take money away from other areas, and they can have many uncoordinated programs. This can cause more work for people and more forms to fill out.

Victorian novels often show many details and focus on rich people. Two books from this time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and strange things. This makes the characters more real. In Oliver Twist, strange events show Oliver's feelings and thoughts. When he dreams about being shot, he cannot control his reactions. He feels scared and sad. He does not try to help himself. He thinks someone else is in control. This shows he is not strong and is giving up. He cannot even try to save himself. This is like the long, quiet nights that pass so quickly and make him sad. /

A few years ago, I worked at an after school program. I helped students with their schoolwork. I was good at English and reading. A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was having trouble reading. I noticed he could say some letters, but others were wrong. He spoke perfect English, but I thought he didn't know the alphabet. I met his mom. She spoke only Spanish. I tried to communicate with her. Then, I realized Adrian knew how to read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well.

I tell this story to talk about the language problem in schools. Even kids who speak English well can have reading trouble. The solution is not easy. For Adrian, it was simple: tutoring in English reading. But for kids who don't speak English, it's harder.

The dual language system can help. It's good for kids who speak Spanish and others. It can even help kids who don't speak Spanish. Many people think it's a waste of resources. But it can help all kids. We should make it the rule, not the exception. We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. But we can have bilingual aids or tutors.

When we are children, many people tell us that there is something bigger than us. Some learn about it in church or temple. Others search inside themselves. Some take the beliefs of their parents. Others reject them. We find our own ways to understand spirituality. We search for light in darkness.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on our porch, listening to rain. He looked at the rain, remembering. He had lost weight. His hair was thin. He did not look at me. I felt alone, afraid. I hugged him. We sat close, looking at the rain.

My father died five days after my birthday. His sickness did not go away. He suffered. I could not watch him die. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not died. I stayed in bed for three days, waiting for news.

No one called me.

The old "Gothic Novel" is like "Old-New" as Ian Watt says in his book "The Rise of the Gothic Novel." People love and hate it. They say it has no real depth, but also love its "terrible sublime" feeling. The first "Gothic Novel," "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, combines old and new ideas to create this new genre. Walpole uses old theatre and nature ideas to make a new story. Gothic novels use old ideas like medieval theatre, architecture, and traditions. The word "gothic" was old and unsophisticated, but the new novel format made it new. The Gothic novel uses chivalry, an old idea of training knights. This idea is in many Gothic novels. Walpole, who wrote "The Castle of Otranto" in a troubled time, thought people had lost the goodness of the old era. He shows this in his character Frederic.

Frederic is described as a brave and kind prince, like a knight. He has suffered and is now believed to be dead. He shows many chivalric traits, like a gallant and courteous knight. This is the start of the Gothic novel's love for excess.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from customer order to raw materials, then to production and distribution. The term was created in 1982 by Keith Oliver. Supply chain management includes planning, doing, and controlling to make customers happy quickly and well. There are six parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give good service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is very important. It starts the whole process. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to know what customers need. After knowing this, managers decide what to produce and how much. They also decide where to produce. They plan workloads and take care of equipment. Every detail is very important. If not planned well, it could cost time and money in the future. I worked at Wal-Mart and Target. Both use designs, books, and processes for everything. This helps them work smoothly.

The second key part is supply. Supply is about making good decisions on what a company can do and who to work with. A company might have many parts for one product. Each part has different equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers decide which part is best. They might also work with other companies to save money or be faster. This is called outsourcing.

A sign says "Hitler is alive in Burma."

Ellen Page, a star, stands alone. She holds a cardboard. A message is on the cardboard. It is written with a Sharpie. Burma is a country. It is in Southeast Asia. The government is bad.

In 2007, many people protested. They wanted a better government. Monks led the protests. The government did not like this. They attacked the monks. They hurt many people.

Many died. A Japanese photographer was killed. The government said only 13 died. But a soldier said many more died. He said many thousands.

This is not new. For a long time, governments have wanted to stop people from saying what they think.

In 1989, many people protested in China. They were killed. In Rwanda, many were killed. Hitler killed many Jews. These are just a few examples.

Duke Ellington's music comes from his long career and his ability to lead his band. He plays piano, but mostly writes music for band members. He lets them play solos freely and makes the band sound good together. He uses voices like instruments. In "Creole Love Call," he uses a voice like an instrument in a slow blues song. He lets other players use their voices too. In "Hot and Bothered," he uses a trumpet and a voice to make a nice sound. In "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)," he uses a trombone to start the melody. He makes all of this happen with his music.

She always felt she needed something. This feeling started when she was 14 years old. She still felt this way at 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. But she was not interested in any boys. Some boys liked her and tried to talk to her, but she did not like them. She did not know why. She thought about this for a few years, but did not find a good answer. She lived her life, always thinking about her feelings.

At home, her parents were calm and kind. They argued rarely. Her parents were good people. She was very independent and had a fun personality. This made people like her.

One day, she heard her mother scream. She ran to the kitchen. Her mother was on the floor in pain. She said, "Ouch, take me to the hospital." She helped her mother to the car. She drove to the hospital. The hospital smelled bad. She was worried about her mother.

Doctors took her mother away. She waited. She did not know what was wrong. Her mother fell off a step stool trying to get a vase.

This study showed that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) can lower the risk of heart disease and stroke. A modified version of this diet, called the "alternate Mediterranean diet" (aMed), is characterized by eating more plants, good fats, and fish, and less meat and fat. A small amount of alcohol is allowed.

Previous studies showed that following a Med diet lowered the risk of heart disease and stroke deaths. A study also found that Med diet was better than a low-fat diet for losing weight and lowering cholesterol in overweight people. But these studies did not focus on stroke and stroke deaths.

This study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years old, who did not have heart disease or diabetes. They were part of the Nurses' Health Study, a large group of nurses. Six times from 1984 to 2004, the study calculated an aMed score from questions about food eaten in the past year. More than 95% of nurses stayed in the study for 20 years. The questions were checked to make sure they were accurate. Reports of heart disease, stroke, and death were checked with medical or hospital records, death certificates, or autopsies. If these were not available, cases were assumed to be "probable" and included. Body mass index, smoking, aspirin use, vitamin intake, menopause status, and hormone use were also calculated. Leisure-time physical activity was added starting in 1986.

To make the results clearer, long-term diet was calculated by averaging scores from two years. Adjustments were made for things that could affect the results, like age, smoking, weight, menopause, hormone use, vitamin intake, alcohol, and physical activity.

A special type of analysis called "Cox proportional-hazard modeling" was used to see the connection between the aMed score and heart disease and stroke risk. Separate models were used for fatal and nonfatal heart disease and stroke.

Following a higher aMed score was linked to less risk of heart disease and stroke. Over 20 years, there were 2391 cases of heart disease, 1763 cases of stroke, and 1077 deaths from heart disease or stroke. Women with the highest aMed scores had less risk of heart disease and stroke than those with the lowest scores.

In 2007, the United States had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, and the housing market fell. Big companies also had problems. The crisis is still happening. We need to know: how did this happen? And how can we stop it?

The crisis started because of bad decisions by politicians. They told banks and companies to give loans to people who could not repay. These loans were called sub-prime loans. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac also helped by making these loans into new things called CDOs and CDS. When people did not pay back these loans, the banks had no money. This made the problem worse.

The crisis started in 1999. The President at that time wanted to be popular to get another term. He made it easy for people to get loans. This made the problem happen later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times said this could happen. He said, "The government-subsidized corporation may have trouble in an economic problem, like the savings and loan industry in the 1980s."

Many things made the economy go down. One was the new types of mortgages. People and banks had too much money in the housing market. When the housing market fell, the banks had big problems. Big banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007. This was about 30% of the USA's GDP. Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold cheap. Lehman Brothers went out of business. Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley had to become commercial banks. Fannie and Freddie had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were put under government control in 2008.

Exposition is not good. It is the part of the story where you tell too much. You should show, not tell.

We all know this. But even Dr. Merlin tells too much. She talks about things that are not important.

In the story, you should tell the reader what happens. But not too much at once. Like in a movie, one character tells another important information. In a book, the author does it.

An example: In a story, you are told the heroine and her husband met, married, and he died. You do not need two pages to read this. You need to show how they loved each other. Show his speech and actions. Show how his life changed her. This will make you feel sad when he dies. And you will care more about the heroine.

Instead of "They met, they married, he died," you should give more details.

Sometimes, it is easy to rush. You want to tell many things about a character. But you do not need to. You should only tell what is important.

I saw two news stories from Columbus, Ohio. The first was on NBC 4 this morning. They talked about a man named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife. They showed his picture and said he looked mean. They gave only two minutes to this story because it was new. The second story was about a young man, Travis Buyers, who was shot. He was critically injured. No one was arrested yet. The police are looking for the shooter. I think they did not talk much about this because he was a black man. I think the news often does not talk about black people when they are victims of crime. The next story was about a bullet hole in a helicopter. The helicopter was shot by a rifle. They said the bullet was .22 caliber. Crime-Stoppers is offering $5,000 for tips. The next story was about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. The weather was going to be hot. They said the story was short because they wanted to use it as a teaser. The next story was about a robbery at a store. The robber was a dark-skinned black man. They talked about his skin color a lot. Another story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin. He was arrested for selling marijuana. Instead of saying he went to jail for 25 years, they said 300 months. I think they did this to make it sound worse. They also said he was Hispanic, but it did not really matter to the story.

There is a strong bond between brothers. It is unbreakable. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else. They see themselves in their brother. When the situation is very bad, this bond shows its true nature, good or bad. These feelings have big costs. To understand brother feelings, we must deal with their results. When we look at our brother's eye, we see ourselves. Our actions and their results show our true character.

In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme. They go on a long, hard journey. They fight and feel many strong feelings. Only one brother lives. The story shows the theme through the main character, Doodle. It also shows through the main character's point of view. This view shows his feelings and how he sees the world.

The main character's actions show one big feeling: pride. He wants to teach his little brother, Doodle, many skills. He wants Doodle to be like him. But Doodle has a weak heart. He cannot do these things. This makes the main character feel sad and angry. He thinks about killing Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him. This makes the main character feel hope. He has love for his brother.

The brain is a complex, creative system that processes information. Technology changed, and so did how people describe the brain. First, it was like a wax tablet. Then, like papyrus. Then, a book. Now, a computer. Remember, these comparisons have limits. They can lead to mistakes.
Information begins with our senses. They change physical things, like touch, heat, sound, or light, into electrical signals. The brain transforms this information. It does this in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up gathers simple information, like color and shape, to make decisions. Top-down uses earlier decisions to speed up understanding.
An attention filter decides what information is important. For example, you notice your name in a noisy room, but not the grass under your shoes. There are many processing steps. The results change with attention.
To process information, it must be stored. There are different kinds of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Sensory memory stores information for a short time. Working memory keeps it for about 20 seconds. Long-term memory stores information in proteins.
There are many ways to think about how the brain stores knowledge. Some use human memory, others use computers, and others use physics. The semantic network model says there are concepts (nodes) linked based on relatedness. For example, "chair" is linked to "table," and "table" to "wooden."

Aldous Huxley criticized the future threats of technology and capitalism. He showed these in his book Brave New World. People in his book value community, not the individual. They are made to want happiness all the time. They are like pawns in a big game. The World Controller decides what they can think and do.

Huxley thought about the growth of these systems. He worried about them. He used words like homogeny and reification. These mean that people and things are made the same and turned into things. Huxley showed that the economy of his time had problems.

Huxley showed how capitalism can trick people. People don't know the real rules of economic classes. They are only interested in their own gain. The common people don't have their own will. They are made to want to spend and consume. The World Controller controls this.

People in the book don't know they are being manipulated. They accept the system that supports capitalism. The higher classes know but do nothing. They accept their place.

In Brave New World, people don't have real relationships. They are shallow. They talk about things like physical appearance. Love and strong feelings don't exist. People accept their place in society. They don't question it.

People are happy to be where they are. They don't try to change. They accept the rules of their class. This shows that capitalism can make people complacent.

I have been a student at University Park for two years and four semesters. It is hard for many people, including me, to move around campus. In my first year, I lived in East Halls dorm. It is far from most classes, like Willard building. It could take 25 minutes to walk to class, especially when it rains. Now, East Halls is not so far from other buildings. There are new fields, buildings, and apartments. But moving around campus is still hard.

A friend of mine stopped riding his bike for a few years. He said, “Bikes are great. They are the best way to get around.” Riding a bike is good for your body and helps you travel far. I live off campus, as far as some dorms. This year, I bought a bike. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, where I have class. Riding a bike saves me time. Walking would take 30-40 minutes more every day. That is 2 and a half hours each week. I need my bike to save time for classes and other activities.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.
